\r\n; ******* Warhead Characteristics *******\r\n
; This is what gives the \"rock, paper, scissors\" character to the game.\r\n
; It describes how the damage is to be applied to the target. The\r\n
; values should take into consideration the \'area of effect\'.\r\n
; example: Although an armor piercing tank round would instantly\r\n
; kill a soldier IF it hit, the anti-infantry rating is still\r\n
; very low because the tank round has such a limited area of\r\n
; effect, lacks pinpoint accuracy, and acknowledges the fact that\r\n
; tanks pose little threat to infantry that take cover.\r\n

\r\n; Spread = Obsolete.  Kept entries to give benchmark for new spread system\r\n
; Wall = Does this warhead damage concrete walls (def=no)?\r\n
; WallAbsoluteDestroyer = Does this warhead do killing damage to a wall, instead of one wound?  (def=no) ;gs\r\n
; Wood = Does this warhead damage wood walls (def=no)?\r\n
; Fire = Does this produce great heat and thus will melt ice (def=no)?\r\n
; Radiation = Is this a radiation weapon?  Certains units will be immune to this. (def=no)\r\n
; Tiberium = Does this warhead destroy tiberium (def=no)?\r\n
; Sparky = Does this warhead cause residual flames (def=no)?\r\n
; Conventional = Is explosive warhead big enough to cause a splash when it hits water [nukes are too big for this] (def=no)?\r\n
; Rocker = Can this warhead cause nearby units to rock upon impact (def=no)?\r\n
; AnimList = list of animations to play when warhead explodes [listed from lesser to greater damage]\r\n
; Verses = damage value verses various armor types (as percentage of full damage)...\r\n
;           -vs- None, Flak, Plate //infantry\r\n
;				Light, Medium, Heavy //units\r\n
;				Wood, Steel, Concrete //buildings\r\n
;				Special_1, Special_2 //dunno yet\r\n
; 3-17 Special_1 is the Shock Trooper\'s electric armor.\r\n
; 5-11 Special_1 is now the Terror Drone\'s \"I\'m a unit with infantry vulnerabilities\" armor\r\n
; 5-11 Special_2 is now spawn rockets\' armor to keep them from blowing each other up when shot\r\n

\r\n; NOTE: (Double Note, a float math bug caused 2% to be used when 1% broke down.  Fixing the bug is why I made 2%)\r\n
; A 0% means no force fire, no retaliate, no passive aquire \r\n
; A 1% means no retaliate, no passive aquire\r\n
; A 2% means no passive aquire\r\n

\r\n; InfDeath = which infantry death animation to use (def=0)\r\n
;             0=instant die, 1=twirl die, 2=explodes, 3=flying death, 4=burn death, 5=electro\r\n
; NEW ONES 6=Yuri head explode 7=Nuke Melt\r\n
; Even Newer 8=Virus explosion 9=Brute transformation\r\n
; Brand spankin new 10=get smashed into pieces by a brute\r\n
; Deform = % chance that this warhead will damage the ground when it hits. (def=0)\r\n
; DeformThreshhold = damage must exceed this amount before deformation can occur (def=0)\r\n
; Particle = Particle effect to use when explosion occurs (def=none)\r\n
; ProneDamage = Damage modifer for infantry when prone (def=1.0)\r\n
; Bright = Does this warhead normally cause a lighting effect when it goes off (def=no). This is overridden in the case of bullets by the weapon \'Bright\' flag.\r\n
; CombatLightSize = % of max size; > 0% means force size of combat light, overriding damage-based value (def=0%)\r\n
; Bullets = Is this weapon a bunch of bullet-like gunfire?  (def=no).\r\n
; CellSpread (def 0)= Replaces Spread and WideDamage.  This is actually how far damage from this warhead can spread\r\n
;   0 will explicitly only hurt the target, anything higher will at least search some cells around and compare distance\r\n
; CellInset (def 0)=Use this to tell autodeploy how much inside CellSpread we need to get before autodeploying.\r\n
;   This way, the desolater won\'t just blast as soon as the target is on the very edge -- he\'ll move in a bit.\r\n
; PercentAtMax (def 1.0)= And this is the percent of damage it does at max range; to control fade linearly\r\n

